tadual Paulista</institution></aff><aff id="aff02"><institution content-type="orgname">PUC-SP/Unesp/Unicamp</institution><institution content-type="orgdiv1">Programa Inter-institucional de Pós-Graduação em Relações Internacionais </institution></aff><aff id="aff03"><institution content-type="orgname">Observatório Cone Sul de Política Exterior</institution></aff><pub-date pub-type="epub-ppub"><year>2008</year></pub-date><volume>51</volume><issue>1</issue><fpage>70</fpage><lpage>86</lpage><history><date date-type="received"><day>26</day><month>10</month><year>2007</year></date><date date-type="accepted"><day>13</day><month>05</month><year>2008</year></date></history><permissions><license license-type="open-access" xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" xml:lang="en"><license-p>This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License.</license-p></license></permissions><abstract><p>Trata-se de avaliar como a aproximação entre os países promovendo a integração regional incide sobre qualidade da democracia e como esta se apresenta no setor de defesa e segurança. A perspectiva adotada é que o grau de estabilidade nas relações civil-militares incide diretamente sobre a formulação e desenvolvimento da cooperação em segurança regional e na estabilidade da democracia latino-americana.</p></abstract><trans-abstract xml:lang="en"><p>Our objective in this paper is to argue the relations between civilians and military in the process of consolidation of the democracy in the South America, Argentina and Brazil in particular and how these countries promoting the integration in the defense and security areas. The perspective adopted is that the stability degree in civilian-military relations directly happens on the development of the cooperation in regional security and of course on stability of the Latin American democracy.</p></trans-abstract><kwd-group xml:lang="pt" kwd-group-type="author-generated"><kwd>Democracia</kwd><kwd>Defesa</kw